rse(\"h1\")?)`.\u001b[0m                                                                \u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m\n\u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m \u001b[37m3. **`tokio`** \u2014 async runtime. Needed once you want concurrent requests.\u001b[0m                                  \u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m\n\u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m                                                                                                            \u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m\n\u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m \u001b[37mHonorable mention: **`spider`** (spider-rs/spider) \u2014 a batteries-included crawler if you want a \u001b[0m           \u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m\n\u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m \u001b[37mhigher-level framework instead of assembling your own.\u001b[0m                                                     \u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m\n\u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m                                                                                                            \u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m\n\u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m \u001b[37m**Best for beginners: `reqwest` + `scraper`.** Start synchronous (skip tokio until you actually need \u001b[0m      \u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m\n\u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m \u001b[37mconcurrency). The API mirrors Python's `requests` + `BeautifulSoup`, every tutorial on the first page of \u001b[0m  \u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m\n\u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m \u001b[37mresults uses this exact pair, and you can scrape a page in ~15 lines. Add `tokio` later when \u001b[0m              \u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m\n\u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m \u001b[37mone-page-at-a-time gets slow; reach for `spider` only if you're doing site-wide crawling rather than \u001b[0m      \u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m\n\u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m \u001b[37mtargeted scraping.\u001b[0m                                                                                         \u001b[36m\u2502\u001b[0m\n\u001b[36m\u2570\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u250